# ADR-0009: Endpoint Relationships and Routing Cardinality

## Status

Accepted

## Context

Workspace Fabric models user intent through resources and coordinates
transactions across independently managed controllers.

Initial development focused on point-to-point routing using the reference
hardware:

- OREI UHD-808 HDMI Matrix
- OREI UKM404 USB Matrix

During evaluation of additional routing scenarios, it became apparent that the
underlying routing model is more general than simple point-to-point switching.

Examples include:

- One video source routed simultaneously to multiple displays.
- Multiple USB devices attached simultaneously to a single host.
- Future audio routing where multiple sources feed a mixer.
- Future multiviewers, compositors, or broadcast equipment supporting multiple
  simultaneous inputs.

The current implementation already supports several of these behaviors through
independent route operations, but the architectural model has not explicitly
defined them.

Assuming every route is one-to-one would unnecessarily constrain future
hardware support and complicate later expansion.

## Decision

Workspace Fabric defines routing as relationships between compatible endpoints.

The architecture intentionally does **not** assume routing is exclusively
point-to-point.

Instead, every endpoint advertises its own connection constraints through
driver-provided capability metadata.

Examples include:

- Maximum incoming connections.
- Maximum outgoing connections.
- Exclusive or shared connections.
- Additional driver-specific routing limitations.

The transaction planner validates requested routing against these declared
constraints rather than relying on globally defined routing assumptions.

## Endpoint Cardinality

Endpoint relationships may include, but are not limited to:

### One-to-One

Traditional point-to-point routing.

Example:

```text
Desktop Display Output
    →
Primary Monitor
```

### One-to-Many

One endpoint may simultaneously connect to multiple compatible endpoints.

Example:

```text
Desktop Display Output
    ├──→ Desk Monitor
    ├──→ Wall Display
    └──→ PiKVM Capture
```

Whether this behavior is permitted depends on the capabilities of the
participating controller.

### Many-to-One

Multiple endpoints may simultaneously connect to a common endpoint.

Example:

```text
Keyboard ─┐
Mouse ────┼──→ Desktop USB Host
Camera ───┤
Microphone┘
```

This behavior already exists in USB routing and should be considered a normal
instance of endpoint cardinality rather than a special-case implementation.

### Many-to-Many

Future hardware may permit multiple concurrent relationships in both
directions.

Examples include:

- Audio mixers.
- Video compositors.
- Broadcast routing systems.
- AV-over-IP systems.
- Software-defined endpoint providers.

Workspace Fabric should not prohibit these topologies unless explicitly limited
by participating driver capabilities.

## Driver Responsibilities

Drivers describe the routing capabilities of their controllers.

Examples may include:

- Maximum simultaneous connections.
- Exclusive versus shared endpoints.
- Hardware-imposed routing limits.
- Bandwidth limitations.
- Format compatibility.
- Additional vendor-specific constraints.

Drivers remain responsible only for reporting capabilities and executing
assigned actions.

Drivers do not make global routing decisions.

## Core Responsibilities

The Workspace Fabric core remains responsible for:

- Validating endpoint compatibility.
- Evaluating routing constraints.
- Detecting routing conflicts.
- Planning deterministic transactions.
- Coordinating participating controllers.

The core must not assume identical routing behavior across controller types.

## User Interfaces

User interfaces should operate on logical resources rather than physical ports.

Future interfaces may support:

- Drag-and-drop routing.
- Interactive topology views.
- Route visualization.
- Route editing.
- Route mirroring.

These interfaces consume the same routing model regardless of endpoint
cardinality.

## Rationale

Generalizing routing relationships removes unnecessary assumptions from the
core architecture while preserving deterministic planning.

The resulting model naturally supports both current and future hardware without
introducing technology-specific routing logic into the control plane.

Existing one-to-one routing remains a valid specialization of the broader
endpoint relationship model.

## Consequences

- The routing model is no longer conceptually limited to point-to-point
  relationships.
- Future drivers may expose richer routing capabilities without requiring
  architectural changes.
- Driver capability metadata becomes the authoritative source of routing
  constraints.
- The transaction planner validates requested relationships using endpoint
  capabilities rather than fixed assumptions.
- Existing hardware implementations remain valid without modification.
- Future user interfaces may expose direct resource routing while relying on
  the same validation and transaction pipeline used by workspaces, scenes, and
  patches.

## Alternatives Considered

### Restrict Workspace Fabric to Point-to-Point Routing

Rejected.

Although suitable for simple HDMI switching, this would incorrectly model USB
routing already supported by the reference implementation and would limit
future expansion into more capable routing hardware.

### Introduce Separate Routing Models for Each Hardware Class

Rejected.

Maintaining different routing semantics for video, USB, audio, and future
device classes would unnecessarily complicate the architecture.

A generalized endpoint relationship model provides a consistent abstraction
while allowing drivers to describe hardware-specific limitations through
capability metadata.
